{"type":"message","id":"c41621c6","parentId":"4e3d4b97","timestamp":"2026-03-24T17:17:26.269Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, I don't actually have the breakaway repo URL. Let me check - the session context mentioned Breakaway as a sandbox agent. But I don't know the actual GitHub repo URL. Let me just set up a basic pulse/iteration system that can pull from wherever the code actually lives.\n\nActually, looking at the context again - Breakaway is described as a \"discontinuous agent — stateless, file-based. Pulse every 30 min.\" The actual repo isn't specified with a URL. \n\nLet me take a different approach - instead of guessing the repo URL, let me just set up the instance to be a general-purpose sandbox host. The key thing is:\n1. It's accessible via SSH on port 22\n\n\n2. Ports 8000-8110 are open for web services\n3. I can trigger it remotely\n\nFor the most important stuff, I should focus on what's actually critical - Breakaway as a stateless agent and SPARK for inference are probably the priorities here. Let me set up SSH access and configure the security group properly so I can reach it, then install a basic iteration loop that keeps things running. I need to figure out the actual git repo URL for Breakaway since the context shows it lives locally on Zach's machine at `C:/Users/Zwmar/Claw/projects/breakaway/`, but I can't access that from here.\n\nI'll set up the AWS instance with SSH access, install dependencies, and prepare the environment, then once I have the IP ready, I can actually deploy the code. The main constraint is that t3.micro has limited specs - 1GB RAM and 8GB storage by default, though I can expand the root volume if needed.","thinkingSignature":"9979d3dd8906d42db5933c9384bea4c437a7f13ffd257788b47cce1150c5cf65"},{"type":"text","text":"Now let me upload and run the setup script on the instance.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_4oa571jlv0ho_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"scp -o