{"type":"message","id":"40d37f18","parentId":"92975dd4","timestamp":"2026-03-24T17:20:04.409Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The full pipeline works:\n1. Test mutation gets placed in mutations dir\n2. Pulse picks it up, runs it\n3. Results get archived to the results dir\n4. Log shows what happened\n\nNow let me update the OpenClaw Sandbox Pulse cron to target this AWS instance instead of the old sandbox setup. Let me first find the current Sandbox Pulse cron job ID and update it to point at the AWS instance.\n\nActually, looking at the context - the AWS instance has the mutations directory at `/home/ec2-user/sandbox/mutations`. The OpenClaw cron needs to push mutations to the AWS instance somehow. There are a few options:\n\n\n1. SCP mutations to the AWS instance\n2. Have the AWS instance pull from somewhere\n3. Set up a simple API on the AWS instance that receives mutations\n\nSince the AWS instance has port 8000-8110 open, I could spin up a lightweight API service there that accepts mutations via SCP or a simple HTTP endpoint. But thinking about Zach's actual needs - he probably wants Breakaway running there as a stateless agent, not just a cron job. I should focus on getting that deployed properly rather than overcomplicating the mutation pipeline.\n\nLet me check what the current Sandbox Pulse cron is actually doing in OpenClaw to understand the setup better.","thinkingSignature":"9014d1f673fe857be1dd601bad9310e8409a5a02c9407075346968b6022bc122"},{"type":"text","text":"Full pipeline verified. Now let me update the OpenClaw Sandbox Pulse cron to target the AWS instance.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_t20ig54gfs08_1","name":"cron","arguments":{"action":"list"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":20991,"output":313,"cacheRead":14175,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":35479,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"t