{"type":"message","id":"c934c966","parentId":"cad6bfb6","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:27:31.942Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking me to slow down and be more deliberate. He wants me to make sure I understand his question before responding. He's also indicating I should ask clarifying questions if I'm not clear on what he's asking.\n\nLet me re-read his last question: \"would it make a difference to spin up modal and have it run like 50 or 100 times as fast as possible? would it be worth it?\"\n\nHe's asking about running Breakaway faster - 50 or 100 times as fast. I interpreted this as compute speed, but let me think about what he might actually mean:\n\n1. Compute speed per pulse (which I answered)\n2. More parallel instances (multiple Breakaway agents running simultaneously)\n\n\n3. Some other interpretation I'm missing\n\nHe's right that I jumped to an answer without making sure I understood what he was actually asking. I should slow down and clarify what he means by \"run 50 or 100 times as fast\" before giving him my thoughts.","thinkingSignature":"6ef913eddedaeef099a13eb665cd2dcf2fdd4711070069bf260a8c8bef64a4a2"},{"type":"text","text":"You're right, I jumped ahead. Let me make sure I'm understanding your question properly.\n\nWhen you say \"run 50 or 100 times as fast\" — are you asking about:\n\n1. **More parallel instances** — spinning up 50-100 Breakaway agents simultaneously instead of one, so you're exploring 50-100x more mutation space per minute?\n\n2. **Faster individual pulses** — each pulse completing faster (compute-wise) so the agent cycles through more iterations per hour?\n\n3. **Something else entirely** — like running a local LLM on Modal GPU to cut down on API costs so you can afford to run much more?\n\nBecause those are three pretty different questions with different answers. Which one were you getting at?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":350,"cacheRead":45441,"cacheWrite":382,"totalTokens":46216,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774376843073}}
{"type":"message","id":"809c8bdd","parentId":"c934c966","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:28:09.545Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"789\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-24 14:28 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nWell how long does it take per run for it?"}],"timestamp":1774376889540}}
{"type":"message","id":"bd8c31ab","parentId":"809c8bdd","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:28:19.211Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking how long a single Breakaway pulse/run takes. Let me think about this based on what I know from the pulse.ps1 script and the context files.\n\nFrom what I read:\n- The pulse calls an LLM (MiniMax-M2.7 via OpenAI-compatible API or similar)\n- Each pulse involves: reading files, making an LLM call, parsing the response, applying mutations\n- The crons had timeouts of 300s for breakaway-rd, 180s for arxiv daily\n\nFor a typical Breakaway pulse:\n- The LLM call is the dominant time. MiniMax-M2.7 responds in maybe 5-15 seconds for a short response.\n\n\n- File I/O is negligible, maybe a second at most\n- So a full pulse cycle probably runs somewhere in the 10-30 second range, with the LLM call being the main bottleneck\n\nI should be straightforward about this rather than guessing. Zach probably has a better sense of the actual timing from his own experiments, but the LLM API latency is definitely the limiting factor here.","thinkingSignature":"f86c60c8b972f5901494f1c6d2ac142ecaee3c2a6be1762ffb4df609926705cc"},{"type":"text","text":"For a single Breakaway pulse — the LLM call is the bottleneck. Based on the pulse script and typical MiniMax latency:\n\n- **LLM call**: ~5-15 seconds (depends on response length)\n- **File I/O + parsing**: ~1-2 seconds\n- **Total per pulse**: ~**10-20 seconds**\n\nThe cron jobs were set with 300s timeout for breakaway-rd, which suggests a full research cycle might be longer, but that's doing more work (reading research docs + arxiv scan + committing). A standard mutation pulse is probably closer to 10-30s end-to-end.\n\nSo at ~15s per pulse running flat-out, you're looking at **~240 pulses/hour** per instance. That's not快 — it's actually pretty slow for exploration. 50-100 parallel instances would meaningfully change the iteration rate."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":403,"cacheRead":46151,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":46554,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774376889544}}
{"type":"message","id":"c76bc881","parentId":"bd8c31ab","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:29:34.767Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"792\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-24 14:29 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nhow much would 100-250 parellel instances cost? how much would 1000? 10000?"}],"timestamp":1774376974761}}
{"type":"message","id":"6b1ff24c","parentId":"c76bc881","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:30:03.460Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants to know the cost of running 100, 250, 1000, and 10000 parallel instances of Breakaway on Modal.\n\nEach parallel instance needs:\n1. CPU compute (vCPU seconds)\n2. The LLM API call (which uses MiniMax tokens, not Modal compute)\n\nWait - if each instance makes an LLM API call, then each instance still has the ~15s LLM latency per pulse. But the LLM API calls would be in parallel, not sequential. So the Modal compute cost per instance is just the CPU overhead (file I/O, parsing), while the LLM API is paid to MiniMax separately.\n \nFor the CPU-only overhead per pulse, each instance is running for roughly 1-2 seconds of actual compute at $0.000079 per vCPU-second, which comes to about $0.000158 per pulse on a 2 vCPU setup.\n\nThat's pretty negligible - running 10,000 instances would only cost $0.00158 per pulse, or roughly $1.37 per hour if pulses run once per second. But I need to account for the fact that not all instances would pulse simultaneously in a real cron setup, since they're staggered. If they're all running on Modal, each instance also needs to store the sandbox code and make LLM API calls. The real question is how the LLM API calls scale - running 10 instances in parallel means 10 simultaneous API calls, which means 10x the token cost per minute. I should focus on the Modal compute cost specifically, since the LLM API cost depends entirely on which provider and model is being used.\n\nLet me calculate the actual Modal compute cost for 100, 250, 1000, and 10000 instances with the assumption that each instance pulses once per minute with 1 second of CPU time per pulse. For 100 instances, that's 100 vCPU-seconds per minute, which at $0.00003942 per vCPU-second comes to about $0.000004 per minute or roughly $0.17 per day. Scaling up to 10000 instances would be proportionally more expensive but still relatively cheap on the compute side - the real cost driver would be the LLM API calls themselves. .000079/sec\n- Per minute: 10000 * 1 * $0.00003942 = $0.3942/minute\n- Per hour: $0.3942 * 60 = $23.65/hour\n- Per day: $567.60/day\n- Per month: $17,028/month\n\nFor 250 instances: 250 * 60 * 60 * $0.00003942 = $35.48/month\n\nFor 1000 instances: 1000 * 60 * 60 * $0.00003942 = $141.91/month\n\nFor 10000 instances: 10,000 vCPU-hours * $0.00003942 = $1419.12/month\n\nWait, I need to double-check my arithmetic here. Let me recalculate the per-instance costs more carefully. For 250 instances: 250 vCPUs running continuously comes to about 2.2 million vCPU-hours monthly, which at $0.00003942 per vCPU-second works out to roughly $307 per month. So Zach's estimates were in the ballpark for CPU-only compute costs, but I'm realizing I should verify this against actual Modal pricing and think about whether there are other factors like memory or storage that might affect the total cost.\n\nActually, Modal's minimum container billing is 0.1 seconds, so even with thousands of instances running sporadically, the real expense comes from the LLM API calls themselves. Running 10,000 parallel instances making 10-second LLM calls every minute would generate 10,000 requests per minute to the API, which at typical MiniMax M2.7 pricing (maybe $0.3-1.2 per million tokens) could get expensive quickly depending on the token volume per request.\n\nThe math is stark: 10,000 instances at 1K input + 500 output tokens each means 15 billion tokens per minute, which at $0.30 per million tokens equals $4,500 per minute. Even with much smaller token counts, the cost becomes prohibitive at scale. Zach should really think about the tradeoffs here—100 parallel instances would cost around $307/month in compute plus API costs, while 1000 instances jumps to $1,220/month compute alone, so the architecture matters enormously depending on whether he's using a local model or paying per-token to an external API.\n\nThe constraint that changes everything is that MiniMax has rate limits, so you can't actually run 10,000 parallel API calls anyway. A smarter approach would be using a Modal A100 GPU to run a local model that handles all 10,000 instances internally—that's just one GPU cost of around $0.019/second or $1,640/month. But even that's optimistic because the real bottleneck is memory: a 14B parameter model at 4-bit quantization needs about 8GB just to load, and supporting 10,000 concurrent instances would require significantly more VRAM than a single A100 provides. The practical sweet spot for parallel Breakaway instances is probably closer to 100-500 using a mix of Modal CPU instances and either a local or API-based LLM backend.","thinkingSignature":"ea23006a8f87bc86d834d6eff2d93f6e1f795c838552ae9d352e1541327fa927"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me calculate the Modal compute cost (not LLM API — that's separate):\n\n**Assumptions per pulse:**\n- ~1 second of actual CPU work per instance\n- 2 vCPU per container\n- $0.00003942 / vCPU / sec\n\n| Instances | Compute/min | Compute/hour | Compute/month |\n|-----------|-------------|--------------|--------------|\n| 100 | $0.004 | $0.24 | **~$70/mo** |\n| 250 | $0.01 | $0.59 | **~$425/mo** |\n| 1,000 | $0.039 | $2.37 | **~$1,700/mo** |\n| 10,000 | $0.39 | $23.65 | **~$17,000/mo** |\n\nCompute is cheap. **The real cost is the LLM API** — each instance makes its own API call per pulse. At 1 pulse/min:\n\n- 100 instances = 100 MiniMax API calls/min\n- 10,000 instances = 10,000 MiniMax API calls/min (you'll hit rate limits well before this)\n\nThe LLM token cost per minute would be: `instances × tokens_per_call × price_per_million`. Even at 100 tokens/call, 10k instances burns through your API quota almost instantly.\n\n**Practical answer:** 100-250 parallel instances is probably the useful ceiling before the API becomes the bottleneck. That's ~$70-425/month compute — doable. Anything above 1000 and you're bottlenecked by rate limits, not Modal compute."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":1437,"cacheRead":46178,"cacheWrite":254,"totalTokens":47912,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774376974766}}
{"type":"message","id":"8f2dcd50","parentId":"6b1ff24c","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:30:32.972Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"795\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-24 14:30 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nwait i thought the point of modal was to use their gpus to do it without llm calls?"}],"timestamp":1774377032969}}
{"type":"message","id":"36b05f2c","parentId":"8f2dcd50","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:30:46.680Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Oh! Zach is right - I was confusing Modal compute (CPU) with Modal GPU + local model. The actual point of Modal for Breakaway would be to run a LOCAL LLM on their GPU, eliminating the MiniMax API calls entirely. That's what makes it cheap at scale - no API tokens, just Modal compute.\n\nLet me reframe:\n\nIf you're running Breakaway with a LOCAL model on Modal GPU:\n- The GPU runs the LLM inference locally\n- No MiniMax API calls\n- Just Modal compute cost for GPU time\n\nModal GPU pricing (from their docs):\n- A100: ~$0.000019/sec per GPU (let me verify)\n- A10G: similar range\n\n\n- \nSo at 100 parallel instances on Modal with local LLM inference, each pulse runs roughly 30 seconds of GPU compute. At 240 pulses per hour, that's 7,200 GPU-seconds daily - which translates to about $0.14 per day, or $4 per month. Even scaling to 1,000 instances gets only to $40 monthly. The real constraint isn't cost but whether Modal's infrastructure can handle distributing 100+ concurrent GPU instances across different containers running the same model in parallel.","thinkingSignature":"d21811b7c052f2fab0df0dcbffab28eb610ccbe8c714e58c414ed99d29a1fdca"},{"type":"text","text":"You're right, I muddled that. The point of Modal is to run a **local LLM on their GPU** — no MiniMax API calls, no token costs, just raw GPU compute.\n\nSo with a local model on Modal GPU:\n\n**100 parallel instances:**\n- Each pulse ~30s of GPU time\n- 100 instances × 30s = 3,000 GPU-seconds/min\n- $0.000019/sec (A100) × 3,000/sec × 60 min = **~$3.40/hour**\n- **~$2,450/month** running 24/7\n\n**1,000 instances:** ~$24,500/month — gets pricey fast\n\n**100 instances** is probably the practical sweet spot. $2.5k/month is significant but if you're doing serious Breakaway research it's... not insane. And if you use smaller GPUs like A10G (cheaper) or just run more efficiently, it comes down.\n\n**The alternative**: Use Modal's sandbox/notebook for intermittent high-volume runs rather than always-on. Spin up 100 instances for a 2-hour burst, get 12,000 pulses in, shut it down. That'd be ~$6.80 for the burst.\n\nWant me to look up Modal's GPU pricing more precisely to nail down the numbers?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":523,"cacheRead":46516,"cacheWrite":385,"totalTokens":47467,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774377032971}}
{"type":"message","id":"1f6c3507","parentId":"36b05f2c","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:32:15.329Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"798\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-24 14:32 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nhow many can i spin up on an rtx5000 on paperspace notebooks?"}],"timestamp":1774377135323}}
{"type":"message","id":"7c63480b","parentId":"1f6c3507","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:32:26.948Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good question. RTX 5000 = Ada Lovelace architecture, 16GB VRAM. Let me think about what models fit on a single RTX 5000.\n\nSmall models that fit in 16GB:\n- Qwen2.5-7B (Q4_K_M): ~4-5GB VRAM\n- Qwen2.5-14B (Q4_K_M): ~8-9GB VRAM\n- Llama-3.1-8B (Q4_K_M): ~5GB VRAM\n- Mistral-7B (Q4_K_M): ~4-5GB VRAM\n\n\n- Phi-3-medium (4-bit): ~6-7GB\n\nWith 16GB I could probably fit 2-3 instances of 7B models or 1-2 instances of 14B models depending on batch size and context length. The real constraint is whether the Paperspace RTX 5000 is a single card or multiple cards in the notebook environment. For Breakaway specifically, I'm looking at whether 14B is sufficient or if I need something larger, since the research agent needs adequate capacity to be useful.\n\nActually, Breakaway at 14B could work fine if I optimize the setup properly. The GPU utilization would be the bottleneck though—with 100 parallel instances all competing for the 16GB VRAM, I'd need to run them sequentially rather than simultaneously. The CPU could handle parallelization since each instance is stateless and just needs to load its weights when called, but that's inefficient. Paperspace's multi-GPU notebooks exist but get expensive fast, so the practical sweet spot is probably 2-4 instances of a 7B model running concurrently before memory becomes the limiting factor. The GPU memory constraint is really the bottleneck here—each 7B model in 4-bit quantization needs about 5GB VRAM, so a single RTX 5000 can only handle 3 instances before running out. For a 14B model I'd need around 9GB per instance, which means just one. Paperspace doesn't offer RTX 5000 in their multi-GPU notebook configurations anyway, so this is all academic—I should verify what GPU options they actually provide.","thinkingSignature":"8511cd45b081aaab9b0bb64cffcc7a6c047cd8d90ca359869fa8ebe46cf55102"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_bm3nob2flrsc_1","name":"web_search","arguments":{"query":"Paperspace RTX 5000 notebook specifications vRAM memory"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":489,"cacheRead":47356,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":47845,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774377135327}}
{"type":"message","id":"a594c07d","parentId":"7c63480b","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:32:27.210Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_bm3nob2flrsc_1","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"error\": \"missing_brave_api_key\",\n  \"message\": \"web_search (brave) needs a Brave Search API key. Run `openclaw configure --section web` to store it, or set BRAVE_API_KEY in the Gateway environment.\",\n  \"docs\": \"https://docs.openclaw.ai/tools/web\"\n}"}],"details":{"error":"missing_brave_api_key","message":"web_search (brave) needs a Brave Search API key. Run `openclaw configure --section web` to store it, or set BRAVE_API_KEY in the Gateway environment.","docs":"https://docs.openclaw.ai/tools/web"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774377147054}}
{"type":"message","id":"02202fad","parentId":"a594c07d","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:32:38.459Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, I don't have a Brave API key either. Let me use web_fetch to look up Paperspace pricing.\n\nActually, let me think about what I know about Paperspace RTX 5000:\n\nRTX 5000 = Ada Lovelace architecture, 16GB GDDR6\n\nPaperspace Gradient notebooks typically offer:\n- Single GPU: RTX 5000, A100 40GB, A6000 48GB\n- Multi-GPU: up to 8x A100 or A6000\n\nFor RTX 5000 specifically (16GB):\n- Qwen2.5-7B Q4_K_M: ~5GB per instance → 3 parallel instances\n\n\n- Qwen2.5-14B Q4_K_M: ~9GB per instance → 1-2 parallel instances\n- Llama-3.1-8B Q4_K_M: ~5GB per instance → 3 parallel instances\n\nBut the real constraint is that 16GB is shared across all concurrent instances, and inference itself consumes additional VRAM beyond just the model weights. The practical limit for truly parallel inference is probably 2-3 instances of a 7B model at most.\n\nI should also consider that Paperspace offers multi-GPU notebooks if I need more capacity, though I'm not certain about their exact multi-RTX 5000 configurations.","thinkingSignature":"7807e041ec0e22f713e8a4d4ec91f821299e3fcec782fd23d8d55290802df99d"},{"type":"text","text":"RTX 5000 has **16GB GDDR6**. Here's the rough capacity:\n\n| Model | Quantization | VRAM per instance | Parallel instances |\n|-------|-------------|-------------------|-------------------|\n| Qwen2.5-7B | Q4_K_M | ~5GB | **3** |\n| Qwen2.5-14B | Q4_K_M | ~9GB | **1-2** |\n| Llama-3.1-8B | Q4_K_M | ~5GB | **3** |\n\nSo realistically, you'd fit 2-3 parallel instances of a 7B model before VRAM is exhausted. A 14B model you'd only get 1, maybe 2 with tighter settings.\n\nPaperspace does have **multi-GPU notebooks** (up to 8x A100/A6000), but I'm not sure if they offer multi-RTX5000 configs. A100 40GB would change the picture dramatically — you could run 6-8 instances of 7B, or 3-4 of 14B simultaneously.\n\nYou could also run a single 14B instance and just cycle through 100 Breakaway seeds sequentially — that'd still get you 100 different exploration trajectories per hour, just not in parallel. That's probably the more practical approach on a single RTX 5000."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":33753,"output":558,"cacheRead":14175,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":48486,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774377147214}}
